.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Pid \- pidfd\-backed process\-exit subscriptions for Linux::Event::Reactor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use v5.36;
\&  use Linux::Event;
\&
\&  my $loop = Linux::Event\->new( model => \*(Aqreactor\*(Aq );
\&
\&  my $pid = fork() // die "fork: $!";
\&  if ($pid == 0) { exit 42 }
\&
\&  my $sub = $loop\->pid($pid, sub ($loop, $pid, $status, $data) {
\&    ...
\&  });
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Pid\*(C'\fR adapts Linux pidfds into the reactor loop. It opens a
pidfd using Linux::FD::Pid, watches it like any other readable filehandle,
and invokes the callback when the target process exits.
.PP
Most users access it through \f(CW\*(C`$loop\->pid(...)\*(C'\fR.
.SH "CALLBACK ABI"
.IX Header "CALLBACK ABI"
Pid callbacks receive four arguments:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $cb\->($loop, $pid, $status, $data)
.Ve
.PP
When \f(CW\*(C`reap => 1\*(C'\fR is in effect and the target is a child process,
\&\f(CW$status\fR is the wait status value. Otherwise it may be \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
Recognized subscription options:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`data\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`reap\*(C'\fR
.SH SUBSCRIPTIONS
.IX Header "SUBSCRIPTIONS"
The returned subscription object supports \f(CW\*(C`cancel\*(C'\fR.
